# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: clos-network
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:clos-network/clos-network] In the field of telecommunications, a **Clos network** is a kind of multistage circuit-switching network that represents a theoretical idealization of practical, multistage switching systems.
[src:clos-network/clos-network] It was invented by Edson Erwin in 1938 and first formalized by the American engineer Charles Clos in 1952.
[src:clos-network/clos-network] By adding stages, a Clos network reduces the number of crosspoints required to compose a large crossbar switch.
[src:clos-network/clos-network] A **Clos network topology** (diagrammed below) is parameterized by three integers *n*, *m*, and *r*: *n* represents the number of sources which feed into each of *r* ingress stage crossbar switches; each ingress stage crossbar switch has *m* outlets; and there are *m* middle stage crossbar switches.
[src:clos-network/clos-network] Circuit switching arranges a dedicated communications path for a connection between endpoints for the duration of the connection.
[src:clos-network/clos-network] This sacrifices total bandwidth available if the dedicated connections are poorly utilized, but makes the connection and bandwidth more predictable, and only introduces control overhead when the connections are initiated, rather than with every packet handled, as in modern packet-switched networks.
[src:clos-network/clos-network] When the Clos network was first devised, the number of crosspoints was a good approximation of the total cost of the switching system.
[src:clos-network/clos-network] While this was important for electromechanical crossbars, it became less relevant with the advent of VLSI, wherein the interconnects could be implemented either directly in silicon, or within a relatively small cluster of boards.
[src:clos-network/clos-network] Upon the advent of complex data centers, with huge interconnect structures, each based on optical fiber links, Clos networks regained importance.
[src:clos-network/clos-network] A subtype of Clos network, the Beneš network, has also found recent application in machine learning.
[src:clos-network/clos-network] Clos networks have three stages: the ingress stage, the middle stage, and the egress stage.
[src:clos-network/clos-network] Each stage is made up of a number of crossbar switches (see diagram below), often just called *crossbars*.
[src:clos-network/clos-network] The network implements an r-way perfect shuffle between stages.
[src:clos-network/clos-network] Each call entering an ingress crossbar switch can be routed through any of the available middle stage crossbar switches, to the relevant egress crossbar switch.
[src:clos-network/clos-network] A middle stage crossbar is available for a particular new call if both the link connecting the ingress switch to the middle stage switch, and the link connecting the middle stage switch to the egress switch, are free.
[src:clos-network/clos-network] Clos networks are defined by three integers *n*, *m*, and *r*.
[src:clos-network/clos-network] *n* represents the number of sources which feed into each of *r* ingress stage crossbar switches.
[src:clos-network/clos-network] Each ingress stage crossbar switch has *m* outlets, and there are *m* middle stage crossbar switches.
[src:clos-network/clos-network] There is exactly one connection between each ingress stage switch and each middle stage switch.
[src:clos-network/clos-network] There are *r* egress stage switches, each with *m* inputs and *n* outputs.
[src:clos-network/clos-network] Each middle stage switch is connected exactly once to each egress stage switch.
[src:clos-network/clos-network] Thus, the ingress stage has *r* switches, each of which has *n* inputs and *m* outputs.
[src:clos-network/clos-network] The middle stage has *m* switches, each of which has *r* inputs and *r* outputs.
[src:clos-network/clos-network] The egress stage has *r* switches, each of which has *m* inputs and *n* outputs.
[src:clos-network/clos-network] The relative values of *m* and *n* define the blocking characteristics of the Clos network.
[src:clos-network/clos-network] If *m* ≥ 2*n*−1, the Clos network is *strict-sense nonblocking*, meaning that an unused input on an ingress switch can always be connected to an unused output on an egress switch, *without having to re-arrange existing calls*.
[src:clos-network/clos-network] This is the result which formed the basis of Clos's classic 1953 paper.
[src:clos-network/clos-network] Assume that there is a free terminal on the input of an ingress switch, and this has to be connected to a free terminal on a particular egress switch.
[src:clos-network/clos-network] In the worst case, *n*−1 other calls are active on the ingress switch in question, and *n*−1 other calls are active on the egress switch in question.
[src:clos-network/clos-network] Assume, also in the worst case, that each of these calls passes through a different middle-stage switch.
[src:clos-network/clos-network] Hence in the worst case, 2*n*−2 of the middle stage switches are unable to carry the new call.
[src:clos-network/clos-network] Therefore, to ensure strict-sense nonblocking operation, another middle stage switch is required, making a total of 2*n*−1.
[src:clos-network/clos-network] The below diagram shows the worst case when the already established calls (blue and red) are passing different middle-stage switches, so another middle-stage switch is necessary to establish a call between the green input and output.
[src:clos-network/clos-network] To prove this, it is sufficient to consider *m* = *n*, with the Clos network fully utilised; that is, *r*×*n* calls in progress.
[src:clos-network/clos-network] The proof shows how any permutation of these *r*×*n* input terminals onto *r*×*n* output terminals may be broken down into smaller permutations which may each be implemented by the individual crossbar switches in a Clos network with *m* = *n*.
[src:clos-network/clos-network] The proof uses Hall's marriage theorem which is given this name because it is often explained as follows.
[src:clos-network/clos-network] Suppose there are *r* boys and *r* girls.
[src:clos-network/clos-network] The theorem states that if every subset of *k* boys (for each *k* such that 0 ≤ *k* ≤ *r*) between them know *k* or more girls, then each boy can be paired off with a girl that he knows.
[src:clos-network/clos-network] It is obvious that this is a necessary condition for pairing to take place; what is surprising is that it is sufficient.
[src:clos-network/clos-network] In the context of a Clos network, each boy represents an ingress switch, and each girl represents an egress switch.
[src:clos-network/clos-network] A boy is said to know a girl if the corresponding ingress and egress switches carry the same call.
[src:clos-network/clos-network] Each set of *k* boys must know at least *k* girls because *k* ingress switches are carrying *k*×*n* calls and these cannot be carried by less than *k* egress switches.
[src:clos-network/clos-network] Hence each ingress switch can be paired off with an egress switch that carries the same call, via a one-to-one mapping.
[src:clos-network/clos-network] These *r* calls can be carried by one middle-stage switch.
[src:clos-network/clos-network] If this middle-stage switch is now removed from the Clos network, *m* is reduced by 1, and we are left with a smaller Clos network.
[src:clos-network/clos-network] The process then repeats itself until *m* = 1, and every call is assigned to a middle-stage switch.
[src:clos-network/clos-network] Real telephone switching systems are rarely strict-sense nonblocking for reasons of cost, and they have a small probability of blocking, which may be evaluated by the Lee or Jacobaeus approximations, assuming no rearrangements of existing calls.
[src:clos-network/clos-network] Here, the potential number of other active calls on each ingress or egress switch is *u* = *n*−1.
[src:clos-network/clos-network] In the Lee approximation, it is assumed that each internal link between stages is already occupied by a call with a certain probability *p*, and that this is completely independent between different links.
[src:clos-network/clos-network] This overestimates the blocking probability, particularly for small *r*.
[src:clos-network/clos-network] The probability that a given internal link is busy is *p* = *uq*/*m*, where *q* is the probability that an ingress or egress link is busy.
[src:clos-network/clos-network] Conversely, the probability that a link is free is 1−*p*.
[src:clos-network/clos-network] The probability that the path connecting an ingress switch to an egress switch via a particular middle stage switch is free is the probability that both links are free, (1−*p*)2.
[src:clos-network/clos-network] Hence the probability of it being unavailable is 1−(1−*p*)2 = 2*p*−*p*2.
[src:clos-network/clos-network] The probability of blocking, or the probability that no such path is free, is then [1−(1−*p*)2]*m*.
[src:clos-network/clos-network] The Jacobaeus approximation is more accurate, and to see how it is derived, assume that some particular mapping of calls entering the Clos network (input calls) already exists onto middle stage switches.
[src:clos-network/clos-network] This reflects the fact that only the *relative* configurations of ingress switch and egress switches is of relevance.
[src:clos-network/clos-network] There are *i* input calls entering via the same ingress switch as the free input terminal to be connected, and there are *j* calls leaving the Clos network (output calls) via the same egress switch as the free output terminal to be connected.
[src:clos-network/clos-network] Let *A* be the number of ways of assigning the *j* output calls to the *m* middle stage switches.
[src:clos-network/clos-network] Let *B* be the number of these assignments which result in blocking.
[src:clos-network/clos-network] This is the number of cases in which the remaining *m*−*j* middle stage switches coincide with *m*−*j* of the *i* input calls, which is the number of subsets containing *m*−*j* of these calls.
[src:clos-network/clos-network] This may be evaluated with *f**i* and *g**j* each being denoted by a binomial distribution.
[src:clos-network/clos-network] Clos networks may also be generalised to any odd number of stages.
[src:clos-network/clos-network] By replacing each centre stage crossbar switch with a 3-stage Clos network, Clos networks of five stages may be constructed.
[src:clos-network/clos-network] By applying the same process repeatedly, 7, 9, 11,... stages are possible.
[src:clos-network/clos-network] A rearrangeably nonblocking network of this type with *m* = *n* = 2 is generally called a *Beneš network*, even though it was discussed and analyzed by others before Václav E.
[src:clos-network/clos-network] The number of inputs and outputs is *N* = *r*×*n* = 2*r*.
[src:clos-network/clos-network] Such networks have 2log2*N* − 1 stages, each containing *N*/2 2×2 crossbar switches, and use a total of *N*log2*N* − *N*/2 2×2 crossbar switches.
[src:clos-network/clos-network] For example, an 8×8 Beneš network (i.e. with *N* = 8) is shown below; it has 2log28 − 1 = 5 stages, each containing *N*/2 = 4 2×2 crossbar switches, and it uses a total of *N* log2*N* − *N*/2 = 20 2×2 crossbar switches.
[src:clos-network/clos-network] The central three stages consist of two smaller 4×4 Beneš networks, while in the center stage, each 2×2 crossbar switch may itself be regarded as a 2×2 Beneš network.
[src:clos-network/clos-network] This example therefore highlights the recursive construction of this type of network, with one of the two constituent 4×4 Beneš highlighted.
[src:clos-network/clos-network] The color of the lines between the 2×2 blocks are chosen to emphasize the odd-even recursive decomposition of the inputs, with the odd numbered inputs going to one sub-block, and the even numbered inputs going to the other sub-block.
[src:clos-network/data-center-network-architectures] A **data center** is a pool of resources (computational, storage, network) interconnected using a communication network.
[src:clos-network/data-center-network-architectures] A data center network (DCN) holds a pivotal role in a data center, as it interconnects all of the data center resources together.
[src:clos-network/data-center-network-architectures] DCNs need to be scalable and efficient to connect tens or even hundreds of thousands of servers to handle the growing demands of cloud computing.
[src:clos-network/data-center-network-architectures] Today's data centers are constrained by the interconnection network.
[src:clos-network/data-center-network-architectures] The adoption of hybrid cloud computing has influenced the design of modern data center networks.
[src:clos-network/data-center-network-architectures] By integrating on-premises infrastructure with private and public cloud environments, organizations can distribute applications and workloads across multiple locations.
[src:clos-network/data-center-network-architectures] As a result, data center resources no longer need to be physically co-located and can communicate through interconnected network architectures.
[src:clos-network/data-center-network-architectures] Data center networks can be divided into multiple separate categories.
[src:clos-network/data-center-network-architectures] The legacy three-tier DCN architecture follows a multi-rooted tree based network topology composed of three layers of network switches, namely access, aggregate, and core layers.
[src:clos-network/data-center-network-architectures] The servers in the lowest layers are connected directly to one of the edge layer switches.
[src:clos-network/data-center-network-architectures] The aggregate layer switches interconnect together multiple access layer switches.
[src:clos-network/data-center-network-architectures] All of the aggregate layer switches are connected to each other by core layer switches.
[src:clos-network/data-center-network-architectures] Core layer switches are also responsible for connecting the data center to the Internet.
[src:clos-network/data-center-network-architectures] The three-tier is the common network architecture used in data centers.
[src:clos-network/data-center-network-architectures] However, three-tier architecture is unable to handle the growing demand of cloud computing.
[src:clos-network/data-center-network-architectures] The higher layers of the three-tier DCN are highly oversubscribed.
[src:clos-network/data-center-network-architectures] Moreover, scalability is another major issue in three-tier DCN.
[src:clos-network/data-center-network-architectures] Major problems faced by the three-tier architecture include, scalability, fault tolerance, energy efficiency, and cross-sectional bandwidth.
[src:clos-network/data-center-network-architectures] The three-tier architecture uses enterprise-level network devices at the higher layers of topology that are very expensive and power hungry.
[src:clos-network/data-center-network-architectures] The fat tree DCN architecture reduces the oversubscription and cross section bandwidth problem faced by the legacy three-tier DCN architecture.
[src:clos-network/data-center-network-architectures] Fat tree DCN employs commodity network switches based architecture using Clos topology.
[src:clos-network/data-center-network-architectures] The network elements in fat tree topology also follows hierarchical organization of network switches in access, aggregate, and core layers.
[src:clos-network/data-center-network-architectures] However, the number of network switches is much larger than the three-tier DCN.
[src:clos-network/data-center-network-architectures] The architecture is composed of *k* pods, where each pod contains, (k/2)2 servers, k/2 access layer switches, and k/2 aggregate layer switches in the topology.
[src:clos-network/data-center-network-architectures] The core layers contain (k/2)2 core switches where each of the core switches is connected to one aggregate layer switch in each of the pods.
[src:clos-network/data-center-network-architectures] The fat tree topology can offer up to 1:1 oversubscription ratio and full bisection bandwidth, depending on each rack's total bandwidth versus the bandwidth available at the tree's highest levels.
[src:clos-network/data-center-network-architectures] Higher tree branches are typically oversubscribed to their lower branches by a ratio of 1:5, with the problem compounding at the highest tree levels, including up to 1:80 or 1:240, at the highest levels.
[src:clos-network/data-center-network-architectures] The fat tree architecture uses a customized addressing scheme and routing algorithm.
[src:clos-network/data-center-network-architectures] The scalability is one of the major issues in fat tree DCN architecture and maximum number of pods is equal to the number of ports in each switch.
[src:clos-network/data-center-network-architectures] DCell is a server-centric hybrid DCN architecture where one server is directly connected to one server.
[src:clos-network/data-center-network-architectures] A server in the DCell architecture is equipped with multiple network interface cards (NICs).
[src:clos-network/data-center-network-architectures] The DCell follows a recursively built hierarchy of cells.
[src:clos-network/data-center-network-architectures] A cell0 is the basic unit and building block of DCell topology arranged in multiple levels, where a higher level cell contains multiple lower layer cells.
[src:clos-network/data-center-network-architectures] The cell0 is building block of DCell topology, which contains *n* servers and one commodity network switch.
[src:clos-network/data-center-network-architectures] The network switch is only used to connect the server within a cell0.
[src:clos-network/data-center-network-architectures] A cell1 contains *k=n+1* cell0 cells, and similarly a cell2 contains k * n + 1 dcell1.
[src:clos-network/data-center-network-architectures] The DCell is a highly scalable architecture where a four level DCell with only six servers in cell0 can accommodate around 3.26 million servers.
[src:clos-network/data-center-network-architectures] Besides very high scalability, the DCell architecture depicts very high structural robustness.
[src:clos-network/data-center-network-architectures] However, cross section bandwidth and network latency is a major issue in DCell DCN architecture.
[src:clos-network/data-center-network-architectures] Some of the other well-known DCNs include BCube, Camcube, FiConn, Jelly fish, and Scafida.
[src:clos-network/data-center-network-architectures] A qualitative discussion of different DCNs along with benefits and drawbacks associated with each one has been made available.
[src:clos-network/data-center-network-architectures] Scalability is one of the foremost challenges to the DCNs.
[src:clos-network/data-center-network-architectures] With the advent of cloud paradigm, data centers are required to scale up to hundreds of thousands of nodes.
[src:clos-network/data-center-network-architectures] Besides offering immense scalability, the DCNs are also required to deliver high cross-section bandwidth.
[src:clos-network/data-center-network-architectures] Current DCN architectures, such as three-tier DCN offer poor cross-section bandwidth and possess very high over-subscription ratio near the root.
[src:clos-network/data-center-network-architectures] Fat tree DCN architecture delivers 1:1 oversubscription ratio and high cross section bandwidth, but it suffers from low scalability limited to *k*=total number of ports in a switch.
[src:clos-network/data-center-network-architectures] DCell offers immense scalability, but it delivers very poor performance under heavy network load and one-to-many traffic patterns.
[src:clos-network/data-center-network-architectures] A quantitative analysis of the three-tier, fat tree, and DCell architectures for performance comparison (based on throughput and latency) is performed for different network traffic pattern.
[src:clos-network/data-center-network-architectures] The fat tree DCN delivers high throughput and low latency as compared to three-tier and DCell.
[src:clos-network/data-center-network-architectures] DCell suffers from very low throughput under high network load and one to many traffic patterns.
[src:clos-network/data-center-network-architectures] One of the major reasons for DCell's low throughput is very high over subscription ratio on the links that interconnect the highest level cells.
[src:clos-network/data-center-network-architectures] The DCell exhibits very high robustness against random and targeted attacks and retains most of its node in the giant cluster after even 10% of targeted failure. multiple failures whether targeted or random, as compared to the fat tree and three-tier DCNs.
[src:clos-network/data-center-network-architectures] One of the major reasons for high robustness and connectivity of the DCell is its multiple connectivity to other nodes that is not found in fat tree or three-tier architectures.
[src:clos-network/data-center-network-architectures] The concerns about the energy needs and environmental impacts of data centers are intensifying.
[src:clos-network/data-center-network-architectures] Energy efficiency is one of the major challenges of today's information and communications technology (ICT) sector.
[src:clos-network/data-center-network-architectures] The networking portion of a data center is accounted to consume around 15% of overall cyber energy usage.
[src:clos-network/data-center-network-architectures] Around 15.6 billion kWh of energy was utilized solely by the communication infrastructure within the data centers worldwide in 2010.
[src:clos-network/data-center-network-architectures] The energy consumption by the network infrastructure within a data center is expected to increase to around 50% in data centers.
[src:clos-network/data-center-network-architectures] IEEE 802.3az standard has been standardized in 2011 that make use of adaptive link rate technique for energy efficiency.
[src:clos-network/data-center-network-architectures] Moreover, fat tree and DCell architectures use commodity network equipment that is inherently energy efficient.
[src:clos-network/data-center-network-architectures] Workload consolidation is also used for energy efficiency by consolidating the workload on few devices to power-off or sleep the idle devices.
[src:clos-network/fat-tree] The **fat tree network** is a universal network for provably efficient communication.
[src:clos-network/fat-tree] Leiserson of the MIT in 1985. k-ary n-trees, the type of fat-trees commonly used in most high-performance networks, were initially formalized in 1997.
[src:clos-network/fat-tree] In a tree data structure, every branch has the same thickness (bandwidth), regardless of their place in the hierarchy—they are all "skinny" (*skinny* in this context means low-bandwidth).
[src:clos-network/fat-tree] In a fat tree, branches nearer the top of the hierarchy are "fatter" (thicker) than branches further down the hierarchy.
[src:clos-network/fat-tree] In a telecommunications network, the branches are data links; the varied thickness (bandwidth) of the data links allows for more efficient and technology-specific use.
[src:clos-network/fat-tree] Mesh and hypercube topologies have communication requirements that follow a rigid algorithm, and cannot be tailored to specific packaging technologies.
[src:clos-network/fat-tree] Supercomputers that use a fat tree network include the two fastest as of late 2018, Summit and Sierra, as well as Tianhe-2, the Meiko Scientific CS-2, Yellowstone, the Earth Simulator, the Cray X2, the Connection Machine CM-5, and various Altix supercomputers.
[src:clos-network/fat-tree] Mercury Computer Systems applied a variant of the fat tree topology—the hypertree network—to their multicomputers.
[src:clos-network/fat-tree] In this architecture, 2 to 360 compute nodes are arranged in a circuit-switched fat tree network.
[src:clos-network/fat-tree] Each node has local memory that can be mapped by any other node.
[src:clos-network/fat-tree] Each node in this heterogeneous system could be an Intel i860, a PowerPC, or a group of three SHARC digital signal processors.
[src:clos-network/fat-tree] The fat tree network was particularly well suited to fast Fourier transform computations, which customers used for such signal processing tasks as radar, sonar, and medical imaging.
[src:clos-network/fat-tree] In August 2008, a team of computer scientists at UCSD published a scalable design for network architecture that uses a topology inspired by the fat tree topology to realize networks that scale better than those of previous hierarchical networks.
[src:clos-network/fat-tree] The architecture uses commodity switches that are cheaper and more power-efficient than high-end modular data center switches.
[src:clos-network/fat-tree] This topology is actually a special instance of a Clos network, rather than a fat-tree as described above.
[src:clos-network/fat-tree] That is because the edges near the root are emulated by many links to separate parents instead of a single high-capacity link to a single parent.
[src:clos-network/fat-tree] However, many authors continue to use the term in this way.
[src:clos-network/network-switch] A **network switch** (also called **switching hub**, **bridging hub**, **Ethernet switch**, and—by the IEEE—**MAC bridge**) is networking hardware that connects devices on a computer network by using packet switching to receive and forward data to the destination device.
[src:clos-network/network-switch] A network switch is a multiport network bridge that uses MAC addresses to forward data at the data link layer (layer 2) of the OSI model.
[src:clos-network/network-switch] Some switches can also forward data at the network layer (layer 3) by additionally incorporating routing functionality.
[src:clos-network/network-switch] Such switches are commonly known as layer-3 switches or multilayer switches.
[src:clos-network/network-switch] Switches for Ethernet are the most common form of network switch.
[src:clos-network/network-switch] The first MAC Bridge was invented in 1983 by Mark Kempf, an engineer in the Networking Advanced Development group of Digital Equipment Corporation (DEC).
[src:clos-network/network-switch] The first two-port bridge product (LANBridge 100) was introduced by that company shortly after.
[src:clos-network/network-switch] The company subsequently produced multi-port switches for both Ethernet and FDDI.
[src:clos-network/network-switch] DEC decided to license its MAC Bridge patent on a royalty-free, non-discriminatory basis that allowed IEEE standardization.
[src:clos-network/network-switch] This permitted a number of other companies to produce multi-port switches, including Kalpana.
[src:clos-network/network-switch] Ethernet was initially a shared-access medium, but the introduction of the MAC bridge began its transformation into its most-common point-to-point form without a collision domain.
[src:clos-network/network-switch] Switches also exist for other types of networks, including Fibre Channel, Asynchronous Transfer Mode, and InfiniBand.
[src:clos-network/network-switch] Unlike repeater hubs, which broadcast the same data out of each port and let the devices pick out the data addressed to them, a network switch learns the Ethernet addresses of connected devices and then only forwards data to the port connected to the device to which it is addressed.
[src:clos-network/network-switch] A switch is a device in a computer network that connects other devices together.
[src:clos-network/network-switch] Multiple data cables are plugged into a switch to enable communication between different networked devices.
[src:clos-network/network-switch] Switches manage the flow of data across a network by transmitting a received network packet only to the one or more devices for which the packet is intended.
[src:clos-network/network-switch] Each networked device connected to a switch can be identified by its network address, allowing the switch to direct the flow of traffic, maximizing the security and efficiency of the network.
[src:clos-network/network-switch] A switch is more intelligent than an Ethernet hub, which simply retransmits packets out of every port of the hub except the port on which the packet was received, unable to distinguish different recipients, and achieves an overall lower network efficiency.
[src:clos-network/network-switch] An Ethernet switch operates at the data link layer (layer 2) of the OSI model to create a separate collision domain for each switch port.
[src:clos-network/network-switch] Each device connected to a switch port can transfer data to any of the other ports at any time and the transmissions will not interfere.
[src:clos-network/network-switch] Because broadcasts are still being forwarded to all connected devices by the switch, the newly formed network segment continues to be a broadcast domain.
[src:clos-network/network-switch] Switches may also operate at higher layers of the OSI model, including the network layer and above.
[src:clos-network/network-switch] A switch that also operates at these higher layers is known as a multilayer switch.
[src:clos-network/network-switch] Segmentation involves the use of a switch to split a larger collision domain into smaller ones in order to reduce collision probability and to improve overall network throughput.
[src:clos-network/network-switch] In the extreme case (i.e., micro-segmentation), each device is directly connected to a switch port dedicated to the device.
[src:clos-network/network-switch] In contrast to an Ethernet hub, there is a separate collision domain on each switch port.
[src:clos-network/network-switch] This allows computers to have dedicated bandwidth on point-to-point connections to the network and also to run in full-duplex mode.
[src:clos-network/network-switch] Full-duplex mode has only one transmitter and one receiver per collision domain, making collisions impossible.
[src:clos-network/network-switch] The network switch plays an integral role in most modern Ethernet local area networks (LANs).
[src:clos-network/network-switch] Mid-to-large-sized LANs contain a number of linked managed switches.
[src:clos-network/network-switch] Small office/home office (SOHO) applications typically use a single switch, or an all-purpose device such as a residential gateway to access small office/home broadband services such as DSL or cable Internet.
[src:clos-network/network-switch] In most of these cases, the end-user device contains a router and components that interface to the particular physical broadband technology.
[src:clos-network/network-switch] Many switches have pluggable modules, such as Small Form-factor Pluggable (SFP) modules.
[src:clos-network/network-switch] These modules often contain a transceiver that connects the switch to a physical medium, such as a fiber optic cable.
[src:clos-network/network-switch] Alternatively, DAC (Direct Attach Copper) cables may be used in place of modules.
[src:clos-network/network-switch] These modules were preceded by Medium Attachment Units connected via Attachment Unit Interfaces to switches and have evolved over time: the first modules were Gigabit interface converters, followed by XENPAK modules, SFP modules, XFP transceivers, SFP+ modules, QSFP, QSFP-DD, and OSFP modules.
[src:clos-network/network-switch] Pluggable modules are also used for transmitting video in broadcast applications.
[src:clos-network/network-switch] CPO is also considerably easier to adapt to water cooling.
[src:clos-network/network-switch] Switches are most commonly used as the network connection point for hosts at the edge of a network.
[src:clos-network/network-switch] In the hierarchical internetworking model and similar network architectures, switches are also used deeper in the network to provide connections between the switches at the edge.
[src:clos-network/network-switch] In switches intended for commercial use, built-in or modular interfaces make it possible to connect different types of networks, including Ethernet, Fibre Channel, RapidIO, ATM, ITU-T G.hn and 802.11.
[src:clos-network/network-switch] This connectivity can be at any of the layers mentioned.
[src:clos-network/network-switch] While the layer-2 functionality is adequate for bandwidth-shifting within one technology, interconnecting technologies such as Ethernet and Token Ring is performed more easily at layer 3 or via routing.
[src:clos-network/network-switch] Devices that interconnect at the layer 3 are traditionally called routers.
[src:clos-network/network-switch] Where there is a need for a great deal of analysis of network performance and security, switches may be connected between WAN routers as places for analytic modules.
[src:clos-network/network-switch] Some vendors provide firewall, network intrusion detection, and performance analysis modules that can plug into switch ports.
[src:clos-network/network-switch] Some of these functions may be on combined modules.
[src:clos-network/network-switch] Through port mirroring, a switch can create a mirror image of data that can go to an external device, such as intrusion detection systems and packet sniffers.
[src:clos-network/network-switch] A modern switch may implement power over Ethernet (PoE), which avoids the need for attached devices, such as a VoIP phone or wireless access point, to have a separate power supply.
[src:clos-network/network-switch] Because switches can have their power circuits connected to uninterruptible power supplies, the connected device can continue operating even when regular office power fails.
[src:clos-network/network-switch] In 1989 and 1990, Kalpana introduced the first multiport Ethernet switch, its seven-port EtherSwitch.
[src:clos-network/network-switch] Modern commercial switches primarily use Ethernet interfaces.
[src:clos-network/network-switch] The core function of an Ethernet switch is to provide multiple ports of layer-2 bridging.
[src:clos-network/network-switch] Layer-1 functionality is required in all switches in support of the higher layers.
[src:clos-network/network-switch] Many switches also perform operations at other layers.
[src:clos-network/network-switch] A device capable of more than bridging is known as a multilayer switch.
[src:clos-network/network-switch] A layer 2 network device is a multiport device that uses hardware addresses (MAC addresses) to process and forward data at the data link layer (layer 2).
[src:clos-network/network-switch] A switch operating as a network bridge may interconnect otherwise separate layer 2 networks.
[src:clos-network/network-switch] The bridge learns the MAC address of each connected device, storing this data in a table that maps MAC addresses to ports.
[src:clos-network/network-switch] This table is often implemented using high-speed content-addressable memory (CAM), some vendors refer to the MAC address table as a CAM table.
[src:clos-network/network-switch] Bridges also buffer an incoming packet and adapt the transmission speed to that of the outgoing port.
[src:clos-network/network-switch] While there are specialized applications, such as storage area networks, where the input and output interfaces are the same bandwidth, this is not always the case in general LAN applications.
[src:clos-network/network-switch] In LANs, a switch used for end-user access typically concentrates lower bandwidth and uplinks into a higher bandwidth.
[src:clos-network/network-switch] The Ethernet header at the start of the frame contains all the information required to make a forwarding decision; some high-performance switches can begin forwarding the frame to the destination whilst still receiving the frame payload from the sender.
[src:clos-network/network-switch] This cut-through switching can significantly reduce latency through the switch.
[src:clos-network/network-switch] Interconnects between switches may be regulated using the Spanning Tree Protocol (STP) that disables forwarding on links so that the resulting local area network is a tree without switching loops.
[src:clos-network/network-switch] In contrast to routers, spanning tree bridges must have topologies with only one active path between two points.
[src:clos-network/network-switch] Shortest path bridging and TRILL (Transparent Interconnection of Lots of Links) are layer 2 alternatives to STP, which allow all paths to be active with multiple equal cost paths.
[src:clos-network/network-switch] Rack-mounted switches may be stand-alone units, stackable switches or large chassis units with swappable line cards.
[src:clos-network/network-switch] It is difficult to monitor traffic that is bridged using a switch because only the sending and receiving ports can see the traffic.
[src:clos-network/network-switch] These monitoring features are rarely present on consumer-grade switches.
[src:clos-network/network-switch] Other monitoring methods include connecting a layer-1 hub or network tap between the monitored device and its switch port.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] Network topology is the topological structure of a network and may be depicted physically or logically.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] It is an application of graph theory wherein communicating devices are modeled as nodes and the connections between the devices are modeled as links or lines between the nodes.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] **Physical topology** is the placement of the various components of a network (e.g., device location and cable installation), while **logical topology** illustrates how data flows within a network.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] Distances between nodes, physical interconnections, transmission rates, or signal types may differ between two different networks, yet their logical topologies may be identical.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] A network's physical topology is a particular concern of the physical layer of the OSI model.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] Examples of network topologies are found in local area networks (LAN), a common computer network installation.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] Any given node in the LAN has one or more physical links to other devices in the network; graphically mapping these links results in a geometric shape that can be used to describe the physical topology of the network.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] A wide variety of physical topologies have been used in LANs, including ring, bus, mesh and star.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] Conversely, mapping the data flow between the components determines the logical topology of the network.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] In comparison, Controller Area Networks, common in vehicles, are primarily distributed control system networks of one or more controllers interconnected with sensors and actuators over, invariably, a physical bus topology.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] Two basic categories of network topologies exist: physical topologies and logical topologies.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] The transmission medium layout used to link devices is the physical topology of the network.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] For conductive or fiber optical mediums, this refers to the layout of cabling, the locations of nodes, and the links between the nodes and the cabling.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] The physical topology of a network is determined by the capabilities of the network access devices and media, the level of control or fault tolerance desired, and the cost associated with cabling or telecommunication circuits.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] In contrast, logical topology is the way that the signals act on the network media, or the way that the data passes through the network from one device to the next without regard to the physical interconnection of the devices.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] A network's logical topology is not necessarily the same as its physical topology.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] For example, the original twisted pair Ethernet using repeater hubs was a logical bus topology carried on a physical star topology.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] Token Ring is a logical ring topology, but is wired as a physical star from the media access unit.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] Logical topologies are often closely associated with media access control methods and protocols.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] Some networks are able to dynamically change their logical topology through configuration changes to their routers and switches.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] The transmission media (often referred to in the literature as the *physical media*) used to link devices to form a computer network include electrical cables (Ethernet, HomePNA, power line communication, G.hn), optical fiber (fiber-optic communication), and radio waves (wireless networking).
[src:clos-network/network-topology] In the OSI model, these are defined at layers 1 and 2 — the physical layer and the data link layer.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] A widely adopted *family* of transmission media used in local area network (LAN) technology is collectively known as Ethernet.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] The media and protocol standards that enable communication between networked devices over Ethernet are defined by IEEE 802.3.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] Ethernet transmits data over both copper and fiber cables.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] Wireless LAN standards (e.g., those defined by IEEE 802.11) use radio waves, or others use infrared signals as a transmission medium.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] Power line communication uses a building's power cabling to transmit data.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] The orders of the following wired technologies are, roughly, from slowest to fastest transmission speed.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] Price is a main factor distinguishing wired and wireless technology options in a business.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] Wireless options command a price premium that can make purchasing wired computers, printers and other devices a financial benefit.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] Before making the decision to purchase hard-wired technology products, a review of the restrictions and limitations of the selections is necessary.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] Business and employee needs may override any cost considerations.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] Both cases have a large round-trip delay time, which gives slow two-way communication, but does not prevent sending large amounts of information.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] Network nodes are the points of connection of the transmission medium to transmitters and receivers of the electrical, optical, or radio signals carried in the medium.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] Nodes may be associated with a computer, but certain types may have only a microcontroller at a node or possibly no programmable device at all.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] In the simplest of serial arrangements, one RS-232 transmitter can be connected by a pair of wires to one receiver, forming two nodes on one link, or a point-to-point topology.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] Some protocols permit a single node to only either transmit or receive (e.g., ARINC 429).
[src:clos-network/network-topology] Other protocols have nodes that can both transmit and receive into a single channel (e.g., CAN can have many transceivers connected to a single bus).
[src:clos-network/network-topology] A network interface controller (NIC) is computer hardware that provides a computer with the ability to access the transmission media, and has the ability to process low-level network information.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] For example, the NIC may have a connector for accepting a cable, or an aerial for wireless transmission and reception, and the associated circuitry.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] The NIC responds to traffic addressed to a network address for either the NIC or the computer as a whole.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] In Ethernet networks, each network interface controller has a unique Media Access Control (MAC) address—usually stored in the controller's permanent memory.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] To avoid address conflicts between network devices, the Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers (IEEE) maintains and administers MAC address uniqueness.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] The size of an Ethernet MAC address is six octets.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] The three most significant octets are reserved to identify NIC manufacturers.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] These manufacturers, using only their assigned prefixes, uniquely assign the three least-significant octets of every Ethernet interface they produce.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] A repeater is an electronic device that receives a network signal, cleans it of unnecessary noise and regenerates it.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] The signal may be reformed or retransmitted at a higher power level, to the other side of an obstruction, possibly using a different transmission medium, so that the signal can cover longer distances without degradation.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] Commercial repeaters have extended RS-232 segments from 15 meters to over a kilometer.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] In most twisted pair Ethernet configurations, repeaters are required for cable that runs longer than 100 meters.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] With fiber optics, repeaters can be tens or even hundreds of kilometers apart.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] Repeaters work within the physical layer of the OSI model; that is, there is no end-to-end change in the physical protocol across the repeater, or repeater pair, even if a different physical layer may be used between the ends of the repeater, or repeater pair.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] Repeaters require a small amount of time to regenerate the signal.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] This can cause a propagation delay that affects network performance and may affect proper function.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] As a result, many network architectures limit the number of repeaters that can be used in a row, e.g., the Ethernet 5-4-3 rule.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] A repeater with multiple ports is known as hub, an Ethernet hub in Ethernet networks, a USB hub in USB networks.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] A network bridge connects and filters traffic between two network segments at the data link layer (layer 2) of the OSI model to form a single network.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] This breaks the network's collision domain but maintains a unified broadcast domain.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] Network segmentation breaks down a large, congested network into an aggregation of smaller, more efficient networks.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] A network switch is a device that forwards and filters OSI layer 2 datagrams (frames) between ports based on the destination MAC address in each frame.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] A switch is distinct from a hub in that it only forwards the frames to the physical ports involved in the communication, rather than all ports connected.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] It can be thought of as a multi-port bridge.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] It learns to associate physical ports to MAC addresses by examining the source addresses of received frames.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] If an unknown destination is targeted, the switch broadcasts to all ports but the source.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] Switches normally have numerous ports, facilitating a star topology for devices and cascading additional switches.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] Multi-layer switches are capable of routing based on layer 3 addressing or additional logical levels.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] The term *switch* is often used loosely to include devices such as routers and bridges, as well as devices that may distribute traffic based on load or based on application content (e.g., a Web URL identifier).
[src:clos-network/network-topology] A router is an internetworking device that forwards packets between networks by processing the routing information included in the packet or datagram (Internet protocol information from layer 3).
[src:clos-network/network-topology] The routing information is often processed in conjunction with the routing table (or forwarding table).
[src:clos-network/network-topology] A router uses its routing table to determine where to forward packets.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] A destination in a routing table can include a black hole because data can go into it; however, no further processing is done for said data, i.e., the packets are dropped.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] Modems (MOdulator-DEModulator) are used to connect network nodes via wire not originally designed for digital network traffic, or for wireless.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] To do this, one or more carrier signals are modulated by the digital signal to produce an analog signal that can be tailored to give the required properties for transmission.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] Modems are commonly used for telephone lines, using a digital subscriber line technology.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] A firewall is a network device for controlling network security and access rules.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] Firewalls are typically configured to reject access requests from unrecognized sources while allowing actions from recognized ones.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] The vital role firewalls play in network security grows in parallel with the constant increase in cyber attacks.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] The study of network topology recognizes eight basic topologies: point-to-point, bus, star, ring or circular, mesh, tree, hybrid, or daisy chain.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] The simplest topology with a dedicated link between two endpoints.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] Easiest to understand of the variations of point-to-point topology is a point-to-point communication channel that appears, to the user, to be permanently associated with the two endpoints.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] A child's tin can telephone is one example of a *physical dedicated* channel.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] Using circuit-switching or packet-switching technologies, a point-to-point circuit can be set up dynamically and dropped when no longer needed.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] Switched point-to-point topologies are the basic model of conventional telephony.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] The value of a permanent point-to-point network is unimpeded communications between the two endpoints.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] The value of an on-demand point-to-point connection is proportional to the number of potential pairs of subscribers and has been expressed as Metcalfe's Law.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] Daisy chaining is accomplished by connecting each computer in series to the next.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] If a message is intended for a computer partway down the line, each system bounces it along in sequence until it reaches the destination.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] A daisy-chained network can take two basic forms: linear and ring.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] In local area networks using bus topology, each node is connected by interface connectors to a single central cable.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] This is the 'bus', also referred to as the backbone, or trunk – all data transmission between nodes in the network is transmitted over this common transmission medium and is able to be received by all nodes in the network simultaneously.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] A signal containing the address of the intended receiving machine travels from a source machine in both directions to all machines connected to the bus until it finds the intended recipient, which then accepts the data.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] If the machine address does not match the intended address for the data, the data portion of the signal is ignored.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] Since the bus topology consists of only one wire, it is less expensive to implement than other topologies, but the savings are offset by the higher cost of managing the network.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] Additionally, since the network is dependent on the single cable, it can be the single point of failure of the network.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] In this topology, data being transferred may be accessed by any node.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] In a linear bus network, all of the nodes of the network are connected to a common transmission medium, which has just two endpoints.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] When the electrical signal reaches the end of the bus, the signal is reflected back down the line, causing unwanted interference.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] To prevent this, the two endpoints of the bus are normally terminated with a device called a terminator.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] In star topology (also called hub-and-spoke), every peripheral node (computer workstation or any other peripheral) is connected to a central node called a hub or switch.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] The hub is the server and the peripherals are the clients.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] The network does not necessarily have to resemble a star to be classified as a star network, but all of the peripheral nodes on the network must be connected to one central hub.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] All traffic that traverses the network passes through the central hub, which acts as a signal repeater.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] The star topology is considered the easiest topology to design and implement.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] One advantage of the star topology is the simplicity of adding additional nodes.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] The primary disadvantage of the star topology is that the hub represents a single point of failure.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] Also, since all peripheral communication must flow through the central hub, the aggregate central bandwidth forms a network bottleneck for large clusters.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] The extended star network topology extends a physical star topology by one or more repeaters between the central node and the peripheral (or 'spoke') nodes.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] The repeaters are used to extend the maximum transmission distance of the physical layer, the point-to-point distance between the central node and the peripheral nodes.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] Repeaters allow greater transmission distance, further than would be possible using just the transmitting power of the central node.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] The use of repeaters can also overcome limitations from the standard upon which the physical layer is based.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] A physical extended star topology in which repeaters are replaced with hubs or switches is a type of hybrid network topology and is referred to as a physical hierarchical star topology, although some texts make no distinction between the two topologies.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] A physical hierarchical star topology can also be referred as a tier-star topology.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] This topology differs from a tree topology in the way star networks are connected together.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] A tier-star topology uses a central node, while a tree topology uses a central bus and can also be referred to as a star-bus network.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] A ring topology is a daisy chain in a closed loop.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] Data travels around the ring in one direction.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] When one node sends data to another, the data passes through each intermediate node on the ring until it reaches its destination.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] The intermediate nodes repeat (retransmit) the data to keep the signal strong.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] Every node is a peer; there is no hierarchical relationship of clients and servers.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] If one node is unable to retransmit data, it severs communication between the nodes before and after it in the bus.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] The value of fully meshed networks is proportional to the exponent of the number of subscribers, assuming that communicating groups of any two endpoints, up to and including all the endpoints, is approximated by Reed's Law.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] In a *fully connected network*, all nodes are interconnected.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] (In graph theory this is called a complete graph.) The simplest fully connected network is a two-node network.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] A fully connected network doesn't need to use packet switching or broadcasting.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] This makes it impractical for large networks.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] This kind of topology does not trip and affect other nodes in the network.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] In a partially connected network, certain nodes are connected to exactly one other node, but some nodes are connected to two or more other nodes with a point-to-point link.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] This makes it possible to make use of some of the redundancy of mesh topology that is physically fully connected, without the expense and complexity required for a connection between every node in the network.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] Hybrid topology is also known as hybrid network.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] Hybrid networks combine two or more topologies in such a way that the resulting network does not exhibit one of the standard topologies (e.g., bus, star, ring, etc.).
[src:clos-network/network-topology] For example, a tree network (or *star-bus network*) is a hybrid topology in which star networks are interconnected via bus networks.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] However, a tree network connected to another tree network is still topologically a tree network, not a distinct network type.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] A hybrid topology is always produced when two different basic network topologies are connected.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] A *star-ring* network consists of two or more ring networks connected using a multistation access unit (MAU) as a centralized hub.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] Two other hybrid network types are *hybrid mesh* and *hierarchical star*.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] The **star topology** reduces the probability of a network failure by connecting all of the peripheral nodes (computers, etc.) to a central node.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] When the physical star topology is applied to a logical bus network such as Ethernet, this central node (traditionally a hub) rebroadcasts all transmissions received from any peripheral node to all peripheral nodes on the network, sometimes including the originating node.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] All peripheral nodes may thus communicate with all others by transmitting to, and receiving from, the central node only.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] The failure of a transmission line linking any peripheral node to the central node will result in the isolation of that peripheral node from all others, but the remaining peripheral nodes will be unaffected.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] However, the disadvantage is that the failure of the central node will cause the failure of all of the peripheral nodes.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] If the central node is *passive*, the originating node must be able to tolerate the reception of an echo of its own transmission, delayed by the two-way round trip transmission time (i.e. to and from the central node) plus any delay generated in the central node.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] An *active* star network has an active central node that usually has the means to prevent echo-related problems.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] **hierarchical topology**) can be viewed as a collection of star networks arranged in a hierarchy.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] This tree structure has individual peripheral nodes (e.g., leaves) which are required to transmit to and receive from one other node only and are not required to act as repeaters or regenerators.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] Unlike the star network, the functionality of the central node may be distributed.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] As in the conventional star network, individual nodes may thus still be isolated from the network by a single-point failure of a transmission path to the node.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] If a link connecting a leaf fails, that leaf is isolated; if a connection to a non-leaf node fails, an entire section of the network becomes isolated from the rest.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] To alleviate the amount of network traffic that comes from broadcasting all signals to all nodes, more advanced central nodes were developed that are able to keep track of the identities of the nodes that are connected to the network.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] These network switches will *learn* the layout of the network by *listening* on each port during normal data transmission, examining the data packets and recording the address/identifier of each connected node and which port it is connected to in a lookup table held in memory.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] This lookup table then allows future transmissions to be forwarded to the intended destination only.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] Daisy chain topology is a way of connecting network nodes in a linear or ring structure.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] It is used to transmit messages from one node to the next until they reach the destination node.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] A daisy chain network can have two types: linear and ring.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] A linear daisy chain network is like an electrical series, where the first and last nodes are not connected.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] A ring daisy chain network is where the first and last nodes are connected, forming a loop.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] In a partially connected mesh topology, there are at least two nodes with two or more paths between them to provide redundant paths in case the link providing one of the paths fails.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] Decentralization is often used to compensate for the single-point-failure disadvantage that is present when using a single device as a central node (e.g., in star and tree networks).
[src:clos-network/network-topology] A special kind of mesh, limiting the number of hops between two nodes, is a hypercube.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] The number of arbitrary forks in mesh networks makes them more difficult to design and implement, but their decentralized nature makes them very useful.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] This is similar in some ways to a grid network, where a linear or ring topology is used to connect systems in multiple directions.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] A multidimensional ring has a toroidal topology, for instance.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] A *fully connected network*, *complete topology*, or *full mesh topology* is a network topology in which there is a direct link between all pairs of nodes.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] In a fully connected network with n nodes, there are ${\frac {n(n-1)}{2}}\,$ direct links.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] Networks designed with this topology are usually very expensive to set up, but provide a high degree of reliability due to the multiple paths for data that are provided by the large number of redundant links between nodes.
[src:clos-network/network-topology] This topology is mostly seen in military applications.
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] In telecommunications, **packet switching** is a method of grouping data into short messages in fixed format, i.e., *packets,* that are transmitted over a telecommunications network.
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] Packets consist of a header and a payload.
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] The header directs the packet to its destination, where the payload is extracted and used by an operating system, application software, or higher-layer protocols.
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] Packet switching is the primary basis for data communications in computer networks worldwide.
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] During the early 1960s, American engineer Paul Baran developed a concept he called *distributed adaptive message block switching* as part of a research program at the RAND Corporation, funded by the United States Department of Defense.
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] His proposal was to provide a fault-tolerant, efficient method for communication of voice messages using low-cost hardware to route the message blocks across a distributed network.
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] His ideas contradicted then-established principles of pre-allocation of network bandwidth, exemplified by the development of telecommunications in the Bell System.
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] The new concept found little resonance among network implementers until the independent work of British computer scientist Donald Davies at the National Physical Laboratory beginning in 1965.
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] Davies developed the concept for data communication using software switches in a high-speed computer network and coined the term *packet switching*.
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] His work inspired numerous packet switching networks in the decade following, including the incorporation of the concept into the design of the ARPANET in the United States and the CYCLADES network in France.
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] The ARPANET and CYCLADES were the primary precursor networks of the modern Internet.
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] Packet switching allows delivery of variable bit rate data streams, realized as sequences of short messages in fixed format, i.e.
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] *packets*, over a computer network which allocates transmission resources as needed using statistical multiplexing or dynamic bandwidth allocation techniques.
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] As they traverse networking hardware, such as switches and routers, packets are received, buffered, queued, and retransmitted (stored and forwarded), resulting in variable latency and throughput depending on link capacity and traffic load on the network.
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] Packet-based communication may be implemented with or without intermediate forwarding nodes (switches and routers).
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] In case of a shared physical medium (such as radio or 10BASE5), the packets may be delivered according to a multiple access scheme.
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] Packet switching contrasts with another principal networking paradigm, circuit switching, a method which pre-allocates dedicated network bandwidth specifically for each communication session, each having a constant bit rate and latency between nodes.
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] A packet switch has four components: input ports, output ports, routing processor, and switching fabric.
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] The concept of switching small blocks of data was invented independently by Paul Baran at the RAND Corporation during the early 1960s in the US and Donald Davies at the National Physical Laboratory (NPL) in the UK in 1965.
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] In the late 1950s, the US Air Force established a wide area network for the Semi-Automatic Ground Environment (SAGE) radar defense system.
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] Recognizing vulnerabilities in this network, the Air Force sought a system that might survive a nuclear attack to enable a response, thus diminishing the attractiveness of the first strike advantage by enemies (see Mutual assured destruction).
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] In the early 1960s, Baran invented the concept of *distributed adaptive message block switching* in support of the Air Force initiative.
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] The concept was first presented to the Air Force in the summer of 1961 as briefing B-265, later published as RAND report P-2626 in 1962, and finally in report RM 3420 in 1964.
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] The reports describe a general architecture for a large-scale, distributed, survivable communications network.
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] The proposal was composed of three key ideas: use of a decentralized network with multiple paths between any two points; dividing user messages into *message blocks;* and delivery of these messages by store and forward switching.
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] Baran's network design was focused on high-speed digital communication of voice messages using hardware switches that were low-cost electronics.
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] Christopher Strachey, who became Oxford University's first Professor of Computation, filed a patent application in the United Kingdom for time-sharing in February 1959.
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] In June that year, he gave a paper "Time Sharing in Large Fast Computers" at the UNESCO Information Processing Conference in Paris where he passed the concept on to J.
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] Licklider (along with John McCarthy) was instrumental in the development of time-sharing.
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] After conversations with Licklider about time-sharing with remote computers in 1965, Davies independently invented a similar data communication concept.
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] His insight was to use short messages in fixed format with high data transmission rates to achieve rapid communications.
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] He went on to develop a design for a hierarchical, high-speed computer network including interface computers and communication protocols.
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] He coined the term *packet switching*, and proposed building a commercial nationwide data network in the UK.
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] He gave a talk on the proposal in 1966, after which a person from the Ministry of Defence (MoD) told him about Baran's work.
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] Roger Scantlebury, a member of Davies' team, presented their work (and referenced that of Baran) at the October 1967 Symposium on Operating Systems Principles (SOSP).
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] At the conference, Scantlebury proposed packet switching for use in the ARPANET and persuaded Larry Roberts the economics were favorable to message switching.
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] Davies had chosen some of the same parameters for his original network design as did Baran, such as a packet size of 1024 bits.
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] Davies proposed that a local-area network should be built at the laboratory to serve the needs of NPL and prove the feasibility of packet switching.
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] After a pilot experiment in early 1969, the NPL Data Communications Network began service in 1970.
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] Davies was invited to Japan to give a series of lectures on packet switching.
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] The NPL team carried out simulation work on datagrams and congestion in networks on a scale to provide data communication across the United Kingdom.
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] Larry Roberts made the key decisions in the request for proposal to build the ARPANET.
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] Roberts met Baran in February 1967, but did not discuss networks.
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] Roberts was known for making decisions quickly.
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] Immediately after SOSP, he incorporated Davies' concepts and designs for packet switching to enable the data communications on the network, and sought input from Baran.
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] A contemporary of Roberts' from MIT, Leonard Kleinrock had researched the application of queueing theory in the field of message switching for his doctoral dissertation in 1961–62 and published it as a book in 1964.
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] Davies, in his 1966 paper on packet switching, applied Kleinrock's techniques to show that "there is an ample margin between the estimated performance of the [packet-switched] system and the stated requirement" in terms of a satisfactory response time for a human user.
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] This addressed a key question about the viability of computer networking.
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] Larry Roberts brought Kleinrock into the ARPANET project informally in early 1967.
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] Roberts and Taylor recognized the issue of response time was important, but did not apply Kleinrock's methods to assess this and based their design on a store-and-forward system that was not intended for real-time computing.
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] After SOSP, and after Roberts' direction to use packet switching, Kleinrock sought input from Baran and proposed to retain Baran and RAND as advisors.
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] The ARPANET working group assigned Kleinrock responsibility to prepare a report on software for the IMP.
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] In 1968, Roberts awarded Kleinrock a contract to establish a Network Measurement Center (NMC) at UCLA to measure and model the performance of packet switching in the ARPANET.
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] Bolt Beranek & Newman (BBN) won the contract to build the network.
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] Designed principally by Bob Kahn, it was the first wide-area packet-switched network with distributed control.
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] The BBN "IMP Guys" independently developed significant aspects of the network's internal operation, including the routing algorithm, flow control, software design, and network control.
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] The UCLA NMC and the BBN team also investigated network congestion.
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] The Network Working Group, led by Steve Crocker, a graduate student of Kleinrock's at UCLA, developed the host-to-host protocol, the Network Control Program, which was approved by Barry Wessler for ARPA, after he ordered certain more exotic elements to be dropped.
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] In 1970, Kleinrock extended his earlier analytic work on message switching to packet switching in the ARPANET.
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] The ARPANET was demonstrated at the International Conference on Computer Communication (ICCC) in Washington in October 1972.
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] However, fundamental questions about the design of packet-switched networks remained.
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] Roberts presented the idea of packet switching to communication industry professionals in the early 1970s.
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] Before ARPANET was operating, they argued that the router buffers would quickly run out.
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] After the ARPANET was operating, they argued that packet switching would never be economic without the government subsidy.
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] Baran had faced the same rejection and thus failed to convince the military to construct a packet switching network in the 1960s.
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] The CYCLADES network was designed by Louis Pouzin in the early 1970s to study internetworking.
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] It was the first to implement the end-to-end principle of Davies, and make the host computers responsible for the reliable delivery of data on a packet-switched network, rather than this being a service of the network itself.
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] His team was thus first to tackle the highly-complex problem of providing user applications with a reliable virtual circuit service while using a best-effort service, an early contribution to what will be the Transmission Control Protocol (TCP).
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] Bob Metcalfe and others at Xerox PARC outlined the idea of Ethernet and the PARC Universal Packet (PUP) for internetworking.
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] In May 1974, Vint Cerf and Bob Kahn described the Transmission Control Program, an internetworking protocol for sharing resources using packet-switching among the nodes.
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] The specifications of the TCP were then published in RFC 675 (*Specification of Internet Transmission Control Program*), written by Vint Cerf, Yogen Dalal and Carl Sunshine in December 1974.
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] The X.25 protocol, developed by Rémi Després and others, was built on the concept of virtual circuits.
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] In the mid-late 1970s and early 1980s, national and international public data networks emerged using X.25 which was developed with participation from France, the UK, Japan, USA and Canada.
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] It was complemented with X.75 to enable internetworking.
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] In the late 1970s, the monolithic Transmission Control Program was layered as the Transmission Control Protocol (TCP), atop the Internet Protocol (IP).
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] Many Internet pioneers developed this into the Internet protocol suite and the associated Internet architecture and governance that emerged in the 1980s.
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] Leonard Kleinrock carried out theoretical work at UCLA during the 1970s analyzing throughput and delay in the ARPANET.
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] Kleinrock published hundreds of research papers, which ultimately launched a new field of research on the theory and application of queuing theory to computer networks.
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] His work on hierarchical routing with student Farouk Kamoun became critical to the operation of the Internet.
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] Packet switching was shown to be optimal in the Huffman coding sense in 1978.
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] For a period in the 1980s and early 1990s, the network engineering community was polarized over the implementation of competing protocol suites, commonly known as the Protocol Wars.
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] It was unclear which of the Internet protocol suite and the OSI model would result in the best and most robust computer networks.
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] Complementary metal–oxide–semiconductor (CMOS) VLSI (very-large-scale integration) technology led to the development of high-speed broadband packet switching during the 1980s–1990s.
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] In the 1978 special edition of the Proceedings of the IEEE on packet switching, Bob Kahn, the guest editor, wrote that "analysis has had little direct impact on the network design problem".
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] In Roberts' paper on "Packet Switching Economics" for the L.M.
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] Ericsson prize for research in data communications in 1982, he referenced only Davies' 1967 paper for SOSP, not the work of Baran or Kleinrock.
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] Kleinrock's paper for the same prize was titled "Packet Switching Principles".
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] In Roberts' 1986 conference paper on "The ARPANET & Computer Networks", he also cites Baran's 1964 paper and one of his own papers from 1966; but only references Kleinrock's work from the 1970s, which addressed the ARPANET.
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] This paper was republished on the web by Roberts in 1995.
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] In 1997, along with seven other Internet pioneers, Roberts and Kleinrock co-wrote "Brief History of the Internet" published by the Internet Society.
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] In it, Kleinrock is described as having "published the first paper on packet switching theory in July 1961 and the first book on the subject in 1964".
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] Many sources about the history of the Internet began to reflect these claims as uncontroversial facts.
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] This became the subject of what Katie Hafner called a "paternity dispute" in The New York Times in 2001.
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] The disagreement about Kleinrock's contribution to packet switching escalated after a statement made on Kleinrock's profile on the UCLA Computer Science department website sometime in the 1990s.
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] Here, he was referred to as the "Inventor of the Internet Technology".
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] The webpage's depictions of Kleinrock's achievements provoked anger among some early Internet pioneers.
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] The dispute over priority became a public issue after Donald Davies posthumously published a paper in 2001 in which he denied that Kleinrock's work in the early 1960s was related to packet switching, stating "I can find no evidence that he understood the principles of packet switching".
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] Davies also described ARPANET project manager Larry Roberts as supporting Kleinrock, referring to Roberts' writings online and Kleinrock's UCLA webpage profile as "very misleading".
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] Walter Isaacson wrote that Kleinrock's claims "led to an outcry among many of the other Internet pioneers, who publicly attacked Kleinrock and said that his brief mention of breaking messages into smaller pieces did not come close to being a proposal for packet switching".
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] Davies' paper reignited a previous dispute over who deserves credit for getting the ARPANET online between engineers at Bolt, Beranek, and Newman (BBN) who had been involved in building and designing the ARPANET IMP on the one side, and ARPA-related researchers on the other.
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] This earlier dispute is exemplified by BBN's Will Crowther, who in a 1990 oral history described Paul Baran's packet switching design (which he called hot-potato routing), as "crazy" and non-sensical, despite the ARPA team having advocated for it.
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] Former IPTO director Bob Taylor also joined the debate, stating that "authors who have interviewed dozens of Arpanet pioneers know very well that the Kleinrock-Roberts claims are not believed".
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] Walter Isaacson notes that "until the mid-1990s Kleinrock had credited [Baran and Davies] with coming up with the idea of packet switching".
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] A subsequent version of Kleinrock's biography webpage was copyrighted in 2009 by Kleinrock.
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] He was called on to defend his position over subsequent decades.
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] A paper published in the journal *Internet Histories* in 2019 supported Kleinrock's view; the author interviewed Kleinrock and Roberts, and did not interview Scantlebury.
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] In 2023, Kleinrock acknowledged that his work published in the early 1960s was about message switching and claimed he was thinking about packet switching.
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] Primary sources and historians recognize Baran and Davies for independently inventing the concept of digital packet switching used in modern computer networking including the ARPANET and the Internet.
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] Kleinrock has received many awards for his ground-breaking applied mathematical research on packet switching, carried out in the 1970s, which was an extension of his pioneering work in the early 1960s on the optimization of message delays in communication networks.
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] Russell said "'Internet history' also suffers from a ... methodological, problem: it tends to be too close to its sources.
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] Many Internet pioneers are alive, active, and eager to shape the histories that describe their accomplishments.
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] Many museums and historians are equally eager to interview the pioneers and to publicize their stories".
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] Packet switching may be classified into connectionless packet switching, using datagrams, and connection-oriented packet switching, using virtual circuits.
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] Examples of connectionless systems are Ethernet, IP, and the User Datagram Protocol (UDP).
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] Connection-oriented systems include X.25, Frame Relay, Multiprotocol Label Switching (MPLS), and TCP.
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] In connectionless mode, each packet is labeled with a destination address, source address, and port numbers.
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] It may also be labeled with the sequence number of the packet.
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] This information eliminates the need for a pre-established path to help the packet find its way to its destination, but means that more information is needed in the packet header, which is therefore larger.
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] The packets are routed individually, sometimes taking different paths, resulting in out-of-order delivery.
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] At the destination, the original message may be reassembled in the correct order, based on the packet sequence numbers.
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] Thus, a virtual circuit carrying a byte stream is provided to the application by a transport layer protocol, although the network only provides a connectionless network layer service.
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] Connection-oriented transmission requires a setup phase to establish the parameters of communication before any packet is transferred.
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] The signaling protocols used for setup allow the application to specify its requirements and discover link parameters.
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] Acceptable values for service parameters may be negotiated.
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] The packets transferred may include a connection identifier rather than address information and the packet header can be smaller, as it only needs to contain this code and any information, such as length, timestamp, or sequence number, which is different for different packets.
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] In this case, address information is only transferred to each node during the connection setup phase, when the route to the destination is discovered and an entry is added to the switching table in each network node through which the connection passes.
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] When a connection identifier is used, routing a packet requires the node to look up the connection identifier in a table.
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] Connection-oriented transport layer protocols such as TCP provide a connection-oriented service by using an underlying connectionless network.
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] In this case, the end-to-end principle dictates that the end nodes, not the network itself, are responsible for the connection-oriented behavior.
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] In telecommunication networks, packet switching is used to optimize the usage of channel capacity and increase robustness.
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] Compared to circuit switching, packet switching is highly dynamic, allocating channel capacity based on usage instead of explicit reservations.
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] This can reduce wasted capacity caused by underutilized reservations at the cost of removing bandwidth guarantees.
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] In practice, congestion control is generally used in IP networks to dynamically negotiate capacity between connections.
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] Packet switching may also increase the robustness of networks in the face of failures.
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] If a node fails, connections do not need to be interrupted, as packets may be routed around the failure.
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] Packet switching is used in the Internet and most local area networks.
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] The Internet is implemented by the Internet Protocol Suite using a variety of link layer technologies.
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] For example, Ethernet and Frame Relay are common.
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] Newer mobile phone technologies (e.g., GSM, LTE) also use packet switching.
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] Packet switching is associated with connectionless networking because, in these systems, no connection agreement needs to be established between communicating parties prior to exchanging data.
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] X.25, the international CCITT standard of 1976, is a notable use of packet switching in that it provides to users a service of flow-controlled virtual circuits.
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] These virtual circuits reliably carry variable-length packets with data order preservation.
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] DATAPAC in Canada was the first public network to support X.25, followed by TRANSPAC in France.
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] Asynchronous Transfer Mode (ATM) is another virtual circuit technology.
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] It differs from X.25 in that it uses small fixed-length packets (cells), and that the network imposes no flow control to users.
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] Technologies such as MPLS and the Resource Reservation Protocol (RSVP) create virtual circuits on top of datagram networks.
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] MPLS and its predecessors, as well as ATM, have been called "fast packet" technologies.
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] MPLS, indeed, has been called "ATM without cells".
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] Virtual circuits are especially useful in building robust failover mechanisms and allocating bandwidth for delay-sensitive applications.
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] The work of Donald Davies in the late 1960s on data communication and computer network design became well known in the United States, Europe and Japan.
[src:clos-network/packet-switching] This was the "cornerstone" that inspired numerous packet switching networks in the decade following.
